<paper>
Paper Title: Theory Before the Test: How to Build High-Verisimilitude Explanatory Theories in Psychological Science
Paper Abstract: Drawing on the philosophy of psychological explanation, we suggest that psychological science, by focusing on effects, may lose sight of its primary explananda: psychological capacities. We revisit Marr’s levels-of-analysis framework, which has been remarkably productive and useful for cognitive psychological explanation. We discuss ways in which Marr’s framework may be extended to other areas of psychology, such as social, developmental, and evolutionary psychology, bringing new benefits to these fields. We then show how theoretical analyses can endow a theory with minimal plausibility even before contact with empirical data: We call this the theoretical cycle. Finally, we explain how our proposal may contribute to addressing critical issues in psychological science, including how to leverage effects to understand capacities better.
</paper>

<paper_classification>
"contribution" = proposes something new (method, technique, dataset, framework, benchmark, etc.)
"survey" = literature review, overview, meta-analysis, position papers (only references existing work)
</paper_classification>

<entity_types>
task      - Problem being solved (image classification, theorem proving, protein folding)
method    - Technique, algorithm, procedure (gradient descent, CRISPR, induction)
data      - Datasets, databases, benchmarks (ImageNet, MNIST, arXiv corpus)
artifact  - Pre-built: trained models, proof libraries (GPT-4, Mathlib, Cas9)
tool      - Software, instruments, platforms (PyTorch, Lean prover, microscope)
concept   - Abstract ideas, theories, frameworks (attention, category theory)
other     - Entities that don't fit above categories
</entity_types>

<relations>
uses     - Anything EXISTING that the paper uses (methods, datasets, tools, concepts, tasks)
proposes - Anything NEW/NOVEL that the paper creates or introduces

VALIDATION REQUIREMENTS:
- ALL papers MUST have at least 1 "uses" (papers always build on existing work)
- CONTRIBUTION papers MUST have at least 1 "proposes" (they must create something new)
</relations>

<output_json>
{
  "paper_type": "contribution" or "survey",
  "triples": [
    {
      "name": "Wikipedia Article Title",
      "relation": "uses|proposes",
      "entity_type": "task|method|data|artifact|tool|concept|other",
      "wikipedia_url": "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/...",
      "relevance": "Why this matters (1 sentence)"
    }
  ]
}
</output_json>

<YOUR_TODO_LIST>
FIRST, add ALL of these to your todo list with "TodoWrite" tool:

CRITICAL: Todo content must be copied exactly as is written here, with NO CHANGES. These todos are intentionally detailed so that another LLM could read each one without any external context and understand exactly what it has to do.

1. Read ./triples_output.json. Classify paper as "contribution" or "survey". Edit triples_output.json to set paper_type field.

2. List ALL triples EXPLICITLY mentioned in title/abstract. For each, determine entity_type and relation.

3. For each triple: Use WebSearch tool with allowed_domains=["en.wikipedia.org"] to search "[entity name]" to find the correct Wikipedia article. IMPORTANT: Always include allowed_domains parameter to restrict to English Wikipedia.

4. Edit triples_output.json to add all triples. For each triple:
   - name: Use the Wikipedia article title (e.g., "Gradient descent" not "gradient descent algorithm")
   - relation: how paper relates to entity (uses or proposes)
   - entity_type: one of task, method, data, artifact, tool, concept, other
   - wikipedia_url: The Wikipedia URL from search results (must start with https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/)
   - relevance: 1 sentence explaining why it matters

5. Run validation: python validate_triple_json.py

6. If validation errors: Fix the errors (use WebSearch with allowed_domains=["en.wikipedia.org"] again if needed for incorrect URLs), edit triples_output.json, and rerun validation. MUST REPEAT until validation passes.

<CRITICAL_WEBSEARCH_INSTRUCTIONS>
When using WebSearch, you MUST use the allowed_domains parameter:
WebSearch(query="[your query]", allowed_domains=["en.wikipedia.org"])

This ensures only English Wikipedia results are returned. Do NOT search without allowed_domains.
</CRITICAL_WEBSEARCH_INSTRUCTIONS>
</YOUR_TODO_LIST>

## Definition and Overview

Cognitive psychology is the scientific study of human mental processes such as attention, language use, memory, perception, problem solving, creativity, and reasoning.

## Historical Development

Cognitive psychology originated in the 1960s in a break from behaviorism, which held from the 1920s to 1950s that mental processes couldn't be scientifically studied. Noam Chomsky's 1959 critique of behaviorism initiated what came to be known as the "cognitive revolution".(no content)Ulric Neisser put the term "cognitive psychology" into common use through his 1967 book Cognitive Psychology.

## Key Influences on the Field

In the mid-20th century, four main influences shaped cognitive psychology: developments in warfare technology during World War II created a need for understanding human performance; developments in computer science led to parallels being drawn between human thought and computational functionality; and Allen Newell and Herbert Simon's work on artificial intelligence encouraged a concept of mental functions patterned on how computers handle memory storage and retrieval.

## Related Research Areas

Cognitive psychology research explores various topics including working memory, attention, language processing, bilingualism, and perception.

## Definition and Overview

Social psychology is the methodical study of how thoughts, feelings, and behaviors are influenced by the actual, imagined, or implied presence of others.(no content)Social psychologists typically explain human behavior as a result of the relationship between mental states and social situations, studying the social conditions under which thoughts, feelings, and behaviors occur, and how these variables influence social interactions.

## Historical Development

In the 19th century, social psychology began to emerge from the larger field of psychology.(no content)One of the first published studies in the field was Norman Triplett's 1898 experiment on the phenomenon of social facilitation.

## Key Theories

Social psychology utilizes various influential theories to explain social phenomena, including:
- Attribution theory – is concerned with the ways in which people explain (or attribute) the behaviour of others.
- Cognitive dissonance – was originally based on the concept of cognitive consistency, but is now more related to self-concept theory. When people do something that violates their view of themselves, this causes an uncomfortable state of dissonance that motivates a change in either attitudes or behaviour.

## Modern Research Focus

Most modern researchers in the 21st century are interested in phenomena such as attribution, social cognition, and self-concept.(no content)Social psychologists are, in addition, concerned with applied psychology, contributing towards applications of social psychology in health, education, law, and the workplace.

## Definition and Overview

Social psychology is the methodical study of how thoughts, feelings, and behaviors are influenced by the actual, imagined, or implied presence of others.(no content)Social psychologists typically explain human behavior as a result of the relationship between mental states and social situations, studying the social conditions under which thoughts, feelings, and behaviors occur, and how these variables influence social interactions.

## Historical Development

In the 19th century, social psychology began to emerge from the larger field of psychology.(no content)One of the first published studies in the field was Norman Triplett's 1898 experiment on the phenomenon of social facilitation.

## Key Theories

Social psychology utilizes various influential theories to explain social phenomena, including:
- Attribution theory – is concerned with the ways in which people explain (or attribute) the behaviour of others.
- Cognitive dissonance – was originally based on the concept of cognitive consistency, but is now more related to self-concept theory. When people do something that violates their view of themselves, this causes an uncomfortable state of dissonance that motivates a change in either attitudes or behaviour.

## Modern Research Focus

Most modern researchers in the 21st century are interested in phenomena such as attribution, social cognition, and self-concept.(no content)Social psychologists are, in addition, concerned with applied psychology, contributing towards applications of social psychology in health, education, law, and the workplace.

Based on the web search results, here's what I found about psychological explanation in philosophy:

## Philosophy of Psychology

Philosophy of psychology is concerned with the history and foundations of psychology, and deals with both epistemological and ontological issues while sharing interests with philosophy of mind and theoretical psychology.

## Psychologism

One important concept related to psychological explanation is **psychologism**. Psychologism is a family of philosophical positions according to which certain psychological facts, laws, or entities play a central role in grounding or explaining certain non-psychological facts, laws, or entities. For example, logical psychologism is a position in logic according to which logical laws and mathematical laws are grounded in, derived from, explained or exhausted by psychological facts or laws.

## Key Philosophical Perspectives

Several major approaches have shaped how psychology explains mental phenomena:

- **Behaviorism**: Behaviorism dominated philosophy of mind for much of the 20th century, especially the first half, and developed as a reaction to the inadequacies of introspectionism.

- **Phenomenology**: Phenomenological psychology is the scientific study of subjective experiences and attempts to explain experiences from the point of view of the subject via the analysis of their written or spoken words.

- **Folk Psychology**: Folk psychology, commonsense psychology, or naïve psychology is the ordinary, intuitive, or non-expert understanding, explanation, and rationalization of people's behaviors and mental states.

These different frameworks represent distinct ways of explaining psychological phenomena in philosophy.

Here's what I found about evolutionary psychology:

## Overview

Evolutionary psychology argues that much of human behavior is the output of psychological adaptations that evolved to solve recurrent problems in human ancestral environments.(no content)Its central assumption is that the human brain is composed of a large number of specialized mechanisms that were shaped by natural selection over a vast period of time to solve the recurrent information-processing problems faced by our ancestors.

## Core Concepts

Evolutionary psychologists hold that behaviors or traits that occur universally in all cultures are good candidates for evolutionary adaptations, including the abilities to infer others' emotions, discern kin from non-kin, identify and prefer healthier mates, and cooperate with others.(no content)Evolutionary psychology primarily uses the theories of natural selection, sexual selection, and inclusive fitness to explain the evolution of psychological adaptations.

## Applications and Research

The theories and findings of evolutionary psychology have applications in many fields, including economics, environment, health, law, management, psychiatry, politics, and literature.(no content)Findings have been made regarding human social behaviour related to infanticide, intelligence, marriage patterns, promiscuity, perception of beauty, bride price, and parental investment.

## Criticism

Criticism of evolutionary psychology involves questions of testability, cognitive and evolutionary assumptions (such as modular functioning of the brain, and large uncertainty about the ancestral environment), importance of non-genetic and non-adaptive explanations, as well as political and ethical issues due to interpretations of research results.
